The stdlib-first answer: use the built-in `URL` constructor — no dependencies needed.

```js
function isValidUrl(string) {
  try {
    new URL(string);
    return true;
  } catch {
    return false;
  }
}

// Examples
isValidUrl("https://example.com");        // true
isValidUrl("http://localhost:3000/path"); // true
isValidUrl("ftp://files.example.com");   // true
isValidUrl("not-a-url");                 // false
isValidUrl("example.com");               // false — no protocol
```

**How it works:** `URL` (available globally in Node.js 10+, no import needed) throws a `TypeError` on invalid input. The try/catch turns that into a boolean.

**If you want to restrict to http/https only** (common for web URLs):

```js
function isWebUrl(string) {
  try {
    const url = new URL(string);
    return url.protocol === "http:" || url.protocol === "https:";
  } catch {
    return false;
  }
}

isWebUrl("ftp://files.example.com"); // false
isWebUrl("https://example.com");     // true
```

**Key behaviors to know:**
| Input | Result | Reason |
|---|---|---|
| `"https://example.com"` | ✅ | Valid |
| `"example.com"` | ❌ | Missing protocol |
| `"//example.com"` | ❌ | Protocol-relative not accepted |
| `"ftp://x"` | ✅ | Valid URL (non-web protocol) |
| `"https://"`  | ❌ | Missing host |

This covers 99% of use cases. A third-party package would only be justified if you need things like IDN (internationalized domain) normalization or strict RFC 3986 compliance edge cases — which are rare in practice.
